{"title_page": "John Hughes (sculptor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = John Hughes\n| image       =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1865|1|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Dublin, Ireland\n| death_date  = {{Death year and age|1941|1865}}<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = Nice, France\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = sculptor\n}}\n'''John Hughes''' (30 January 1865 \u2013 1941) was an Irish [[sculpture|sculptor]].\n\n==Life==\nHughes was born in [[Dublin]] and educated at North Richmond Street [[Irish Christian Brothers|CBS]]. He entered the [[National College of Art and Design|Metropolitan School of Art]] in Dublin in 1878 and trained as a part-time student for ten years. In 1890 he won a scholarship to the [[South Kensington School of Art]], London, after which another scholarship took him to Paris. He then studied further in Italy. He was appointed as teacher to the Metropolitan School of Art in Dublin in 1894 and in 1902 became Professor of Sculpture in the [[Royal Hibernian Academy]] School. His last residence in Dublin was at 28 Lennox Street, [[Portobello, Dublin|Portobello]]. From 1903 he lived in Italy and in France; he died at [[Nice]] in 1941.\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Queen Victoria \"visits\" Library Towers (8409924813).jpg|thumb|right|Statue of Queen Victoria in front of the [[National Library of Ireland]] (circa 1908)]]\nIn Ireland:\n*''Man of Sorrow''; ''Madonna and Child'', both 1901, for Loughrea Cathedral\n*''A dying Irish soldier overlooked by Erin'', now in the garden of [[Dublin Castle]] Conference Centre\n*''Monument to Charles Kickham'', in [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]].\nOthers:\n*''W. E. Gladstone Memorial'', intended for the [[Phoenix Park]], but installed instead at [[Hawarden Castle (18th century)|Hawarden]] in 1925.\n*''[[Statue of Queen Victoria, Sydney|Queen Victoria]]'', unveiled by King Edward VII in 1904 outside [[Leinster House]] in Dublin, re-erected in Sydney, Australia in 1987. This bronze statue was cast by the Parlanti Foundry of London.<ref>found on letterhead of A Parlanti in private collection</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{No footnotes|date=February 2009}}\n\n==External links==\n*Alan Denson: ''John Hughes, sculptor, 1865-1941: A documentary biography''.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hughes, John}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish sculptors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the National College of Art and Design]]\n\n{{Ireland-sculptor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = John Hughes\n| image       =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1865|1|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Dublin, Ireland\n| death_date  = {{Death year and age|1941|1865}}<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = Nice, France\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = sculptor\n}}\n'''John Hughes''' (30 January 1865 \u2013 1941) was an Irish [[sculpture|sculptor]].\n\n==Life==\nHughes was born in [[Dublin]] and educated at North Richmond Street [[Irish Christian Brothers|CBS]]. He entered the [[National College of Art and Design|Metropolitan School of Art]] in Dublin in 1878 and trained as a part-time student for ten years. In 1890 he won a scholarship to the [[South Kensington School of Art]], London, after which another scholarship took him to Paris. He then studied further in Italy. He was appointed as teacher to the Metropolitan School of Art in Dublin in 1894 and in 1902 became Professor of Sculpture in the [[Royal Hibernian Academy]] School. His last residence in Dublin was at 28 Lennox Street, [[Portobello, Dublin|Portobello]]. From 1903 he lived in Italy and in France; he died at [[Nice]] in 1941.\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Queen Victoria \"visits\" Library Towers (8409924813).jpg|thumb|right|Statue of Queen Victoria in front of the [[National Library of Ireland]] (circa 1908)]]\nIn Ireland:\n*''Man of Sorrow''; ''Madonna and Child'', both 1901, for Loughrea Cathedral\n*''A dying Irish soldier overlooked by Erin'', now in the garden of [[Dublin Castle]] Conference Centre\n*''Monument to Charles Kickham'', in [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]].\nOthers:\n*''W. E. Gladstone Memorial'', intended for the [[Phoenix Park]], but installed instead at [[Hawarden Castle (18th century)|Hawarden]] in 1925.\n*''[[Statue of Queen Victoria, Sydney|Queen Victoria]]'', unveiled by King Edward VII in 1904 outside [[Leinster House]] in Dublin, re-erected in Sydney, Australia in 1987.\n\n==References==\n{{No footnotes|date=February 2009}}\n\n==External links==\n*Alan Denson: ''John Hughes, sculptor, 1865-1941: A documentary biography''.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hughes, John}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish sculptors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the National College of Art and Design]]\n\n{{Ireland-sculptor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Steve Parlanti", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Hughes_(sculptor)"}
{"title_page": "Rescued from an Eagle's Nest", "text_new": "{{short description|1908 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rescued from an Eagle's Nest\n| image          = Rescued from an eagle's nest still.jpg\n| caption        = Still from the film\n| director       = [[J. Searle Dawley]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Henry B. Walthall]]\n| cinematography = [[Edwin S. Porter]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = Edison Film Company\n| released       = {{film date|1908|1|16}}\n| runtime        = 6 minutes \n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent with English intertitles\n}}\n[[File:Rescued from an Eagle's Nest (1908).webm|thumb|thumbtime=1|upright=1.5|''Rescued from an Eagle's Nest'']]\n'''''Rescued from an Eagle's Nest''''' is a 1908 American [[silent film|silent]] action-[[drama]] co-directed by [[Edwin S Porter]] and [[J. Searle Dawley]] for the Edison film studios.\n\nThis film features the first acting performance of the seminal American filmmaker [[D. W. Griffith]], whose directorial debut was released later that year. In the opening scene, he exits a cabin. This appearance was prompted by being both broke and stranded in New York after the failure of a play he authored. He responded to an Edison studios offer of $15 per treatment with a script idea which was based on the Puccini opera, Tosca. Porter rejected Griffith's treatment then offered him the lead role in this production. Six months later he directed his first film for Biograph. Only one other film in which Griffith appears as an actor survives. A print of ''Rescue'' survives in the [[Museum of Modern Art]] film archive.<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/R/RescuedFromAnEaglesNes1908.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: Rescued from an Eagle's Nest |accessdate=November 29, 2009|work=Silent Era}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA woodsman leaves a hut followed by a woman with their baby. Nearby some men chop down a tree. The baby is left outside the hut, but an eagle flies away with it. The mother comes outside and sees what has happened. She picks up a gun and aims, but decides against it. She tells the woodmen and they get to the cliff where the eagle's nest is. One of the men is let down on a rope to the nest. However the eagle attacks, but he kills it and kicks it off the cliff. He then picks up the baby, is hoisted up the cliff, and returns the baby to its mother.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[D. W. Griffith]] as Father\n* [[Henry B. Walthall]] as Woodsman (as H. B. Walthall)\n* Miss Earle\n* Jinnie Frazer as Baby\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1908]]\n* [[1908 in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0000749|title=Rescued from an Eagle's Nest}}\n\n{{J. Searle Dawley}}\n\n[[Category:1908 films]]\n[[Category:1900s drama films]]\n[[Category:1900s short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by J. Searle Dawley]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Fort Lee]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n\n{{1900s-drama-film-stub}}\n{{short-silent-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1908 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rescued from an Eagle's Nest\n| image          = Rescued from an eagle's nest still.jpg\n| caption        = Still from the film\n| director       = [[J. Searle Dawley]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Henry B. Walthall]]\n| cinematography = [[Edwin S. Porter]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = [[Biograph Company]]\n| released       = {{film date|1908|1|16}}\n| runtime        = 6 minutes \n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent with English intertitles\n}}\n[[File:Rescued from an Eagle's Nest (1908).webm|thumb|thumbtime=1|upright=1.5|''Rescued from an Eagle's Nest'']]\n'''''Rescued from an Eagle's Nest''''' is a 1908 American [[silent film|silent]] action-[[drama]] co-directed by [[Edwin S Porter]] and [[J. Searle Dawley]] for the Edison film studios.\n\nThis film features the first acting performance of the seminal American filmmaker [[D. W. Griffith]], whose directorial debut was released later that year. In the opening scene, he exits a cabin. This appearance was prompted by being both broke and stranded in New York after the failure of a play he authored. He responded to an Edison studios offer of $15 per treatment with a script idea which was based on the Puccini opera, Tosca. Porter rejected Griffith's treatment then offered him the lead role in this production. Six months later he directed his first film for Biograph. Only one other film in which Griffith appears as an actor survives. A print of ''Rescue'' survives in the [[Museum of Modern Art]] film archive.<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/R/RescuedFromAnEaglesNes1908.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: Rescued from an Eagle's Nest |accessdate=November 29, 2009|work=Silent Era}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA woodsman leaves a hut followed by a woman with their baby. Nearby some men chop down a tree. The baby is left outside the hut, but an eagle flies away with it. The mother comes outside and sees what has happened. She picks up a gun and aims, but decides against it. She tells the woodmen and they get to the cliff where the eagle's nest is. One of the men is let down on a rope to the nest. However the eagle attacks, but he kills it and kicks it off the cliff. He then picks up the baby, is hoisted up the cliff, and returns the baby to its mother.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[D. W. Griffith]] as Father\n* [[Henry B. Walthall]] as Woodsman (as H. B. Walthall)\n* Miss Earle\n* Jinnie Frazer as Baby\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1908]]\n* [[1908 in film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0000749|title=Rescued from an Eagle's Nest}}\n\n{{J. Searle Dawley}}\n\n[[Category:1908 films]]\n[[Category:1900s drama films]]\n[[Category:1900s short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by J. Searle Dawley]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Fort Lee]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n\n{{1900s-drama-film-stub}}\n{{short-silent-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jimknut", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rescued_from_an_Eagle%27s_Nest"}
{"title_page": "Turkey\u2013United States relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Turkey and the United States of America}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations|Turkish\u2013American|Turkey|USA|filetype=svg|mission1=[[Embassy of Turkey, Washington, D.C.|Turkish Embassy, Washington D.C.]]|mission2=[[Embassy of the United States, Ankara|United States Embassy, Ankara]]}}\n'''Turkey\u2013United States relations''' are [[bilateral relations]] between [[Turkey]] and the [[United States]]. Relations in the post-World War II period evolved from the [[Second Cairo Conference]] in December 1943 and Turkey's entrance into World War II on the side of the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in February 1945. Later that year, Turkey became a charter member of the [[United Nations]].<ref name=\"Turkey_UN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/Overview/growth.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061026194057/https://www.un.org/Overview/growth.htm|archive-date=26 October 2006|title=Growth in United Nations membership (1945\u20132005)|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=2006-10-30|date=2006-07-03}}</ref> Difficulties faced by Greece after the war in quelling a communist rebellion, along with [[Turkish Straits crisis|demands]] by the Soviet Union for military bases in the [[Turkish Straits]], prompted the United States to declare the [[Truman Doctrine]] in 1947. The doctrine enunciated American intentions to guarantee the security of Turkey and Greece, and resulted in significant U.S. military and economic support.<ref name=\"Truman Doctrine\" >{{cite book|title=Outposts and Allies: U.S. Army Logistics in the Cold War, 1945-1953|first=James A|last=Huston|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|location= |year=1988|isbn=0-941664-84-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ID4E3Lm8TsgC&pg=PA198&lpg=PA198&dq=turkey+cold+war|page=198}}</ref> This support manifested in the establishment of a clandestine [[stay-behind]] army, denoted the \"[[Counter-Guerrilla]]\", under [[Operation Gladio]]. After participating with United Nations forces in the [[Korean War]], Turkey joined the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] in 1952.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_52044.htm |title=Member countries |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 10, 2016  |website=nato.int |publisher=[[NATO]] |access-date=August 24, 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nRelations between the countries began to deteriorate in 2003 as Turkey refused to allow the United States to use [[Incirlik Air Base]] for the [[Iraq War|invasion of Iraq]], a process that intensified following the failed [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] in Turkey in July 2016 as the country\u2032s foreign policy has gradually re-orientated towards seeking partnerships with other powers such as [[Russia]].<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-03/u-s-sanctions-against-nato-ally-turkey-puts-ties-at-crossroads U.S. Sanctions Against NATO Ally Turkey Put Ties at Crossroads] Bloomberg, 3 August 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/11/turkey-ever-closer-ties-with-russia-leave-us-lacking-key-ally-on-syria Turkey's ever-closer ties with Russia leave US lacking key ally on Syria] The Guardian, 11 April 2018.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yegin|first=Mehmet|title=Turkey-U.S. Relations: Towards a Multidimentional Partnership (May 2013)|url=https://www.academia.edu/5461662}}</ref>\n\nA 2017 survey conducted by the [[Pew Research Center]] showed 79% of Turks had a negative view of the United States, with only 18% having a positive view.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2017/06/26/tarnished-american-brand/ |title = Trump Unpopular Worldwide, American Image Suffers|date = 2017-06-26}}</ref> The same study also showed only 11% of Turks had confidence in the current US leader, President Donald Trump,<ref>{{cite news|title=Amid tension, Trump and Turkey's Erdogan agree to strengthen ties|url=http://www.muslimglobal.com/2017/09/amid-tension-trump-and-turkeys-erdogan.html|accessdate=9 September 2017|publisher=Muslim Global}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2017/06/26/u-s-image-suffers-as-publics-around-world-question-trumps-leadership/ | title=Trump Unpopular Worldwide, American Image Suffers| date=2017-06-26}}</ref>  with 82% having no confidence in him.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2017/06/26/worldwide-few-confident-in-trump-or-his-policies/ |title = Trump Unpopular Worldwide, American Image Suffers|date = 2017-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Country comparison==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n! Common name !! [[Turkey]] !! [[United States]]\n|-\n! Official name !! Republic of Turkey!! United States of America\n|-\n| Coat of arms\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | \n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:Great Seal of the United States (obverse).svg|145px]]\n|-\n| Flag\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Turkey|size=125px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|America|size=155px|text=none}}\n|-\n| [[List of countries and dependencies by area|Area]]\n| 783,356 km2 (302,455 sq mi) (36th)\n| 9,525,067&nbsp;km\u00b2 (3,794,083 sq mi)\n(including [[Alaska]] and [[Hawaii]])<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Gopnik |first=Adam |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/United-States |title=United States |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica online |year=2018 |accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[List of countries by population|Population]]\n| 82,003,882[2] (19th)\n| 329,798,310\n|-\n| [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories by population density|Population density]]\n| 105[3]/km2 (271.9/sq mi) (107th)\n| 32.8/km2 (85/sq mi)\n|-\n| [[List of national capitals|Capital]]\n| [[Ankara]]\n| [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|-\n| [[List of cities proper by population|Largest city]]\n| [[List of largest cities and towns in Turkey|Istanbul]] (20,000,000)\n| [[List of United States urban areas|New York City]] (8,622,698)\n|-\n| Government\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Multiparty state|multi-party]] [[democratic system|democratic]] [[republic]]\n| [[Federalism|Federal]] [[democratic system|democratic]] [[republic]]\n|-\n| First Leader\n| [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]]\n| [[George Washington]]\n|-\n| Current Leader\n| [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]\n| [[Donald Trump]]\n|-\n| Current Vice Leader  \n| [[Fuat Oktay]]\n| [[Mike Pence]]\n|-\n| Current Foreign Minister\n| [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]]  \n| [[Mike Pompeo]]            \n|-\n|Current Defence Minister\n| [[Hulusi Akar]]\n| [[Mark Esper]] \n|-\n| Established\n|24 July 1923 ([[Treaty of Lausanne|Republic of Turkey recognized]])<br />\n|4 July 1776 ([[United States Declaration of Independence|independence declared]])<br />\n3 September 1783 ([[Treaty of Paris (1783)|independence recognized]])<br />\n21 June 1788 ([[United States Constitution|current constitution]])\n|-\n|Official languages\n| [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n| None at the federal level ([[English language|English]] ''de facto'')\n|-\n|Currency\n| [[Turkish lira]] (\u20ba) (TRY)\n| [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]]\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP|GDP (nominal)]]\n| $2.274 trillion[4] (13th) (2018)\n| $20.891 trillion (2018)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by external debt|External debt (nominal)]]\n| $1.843 trillion (2018 Q4)\n| $20.740 trillion (2018 Q4)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|GDP (PPP)]]\n| \n| $20.891 trillion (2018)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|GDP (nominal) per capita]]\n| \n| $62,518 (2018)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP (PPP) per capita]]\n| $9,346[4] (2018)\n| $62,518 (2018)\n|-\n| [[List of countries by Human Development Index|Human Development Index]]\n| \n| 0.924 (<span style=\"color:#006000;\">very high</span>)\n|-\n| [[Expatriates]]\n| \n| ~5,025,817<ref name=\"usasurveys2017\">{{cite web |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableserv