3/1973  till: 06/04/1973 color:acting     text:\"[[Tekin Ar\u0131burun|Ar\u0131burun]]\" \n  from: 06/04/1973  till: 07/04/1980 color:president  text:\"[[Fahri Korut\u00fcrk|Korut\u00fcrk]]\" shift:(0,10)\n  from: 07/04/1980  till: 12/09/1980 color:acting     text:\"[[\u0130hsan Sabri \u00c7a\u011flayangil|\u00c7a\u011flayangil]]\" \n  from: 12/09/1980  till: 09/11/1982 color:military   text:\"[[Kenan Evren|Evren]]\" shift:(0,10)\n  from: 09/11/1982  till: 09/11/1989 color:president  text:\"[[Kenan Evren|Evren]]\" \n  from: 09/11/1989  till: 17/04/1993 color:president  text:\"[[Turgut \u00d6zal|\u00d6zal]]\" \n  from: 17/04/1993  till: 16/05/1993 color:acting     text:\"[[H\u00fcsamettin Cindoruk|Cindoruk]]\" shift:(0,10)\n  from: 16/05/1993  till: 16/05/2000 color:president  text:\"[[S\u00fcleyman Demirel|Demirel]]\"\n  from: 16/05/2000  till: 28/08/2007 color:president  text:\"[[Ahmet Necdet Sezer|Sezer]]\" \n  from: 28/08/2007  till: 28/08/2014 color:president  text:\"[[Abdullah G\u00fcl|G\u00fcl]]\" \n  from: 28/08/2014  till: 24/06/2018 color:president  text:\"[[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]]\" shift:(0,10)\n  from: 24/06/2018  till: $now       color:executive  text:\"[[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]]\"\n\n  bar:us\n  from: 20/01/2017 till: $now color:gop text:\"[[Donald Trump|Trump]]\"\n  from: 20/01/2009 till: 20/01/2017  color:dem  text:\"[[Barack Obama|Obama]]\"\n  from: 20/01/2001 till: 20/01/2009  color:gop  text:\"[[George W. Bush|G.W. Bush]]\"\n  from: 20/01/1993 till: 20/01/2001  color:dem  text:\"[[Bill Clinton|Clinton]]\"\n  from: 20/01/1989 till: 20/01/1993  color:gop  text:\"[[George H. W. Bush|G.H.W. Bush]]\"\n  from: 20/01/1981 till: 20/01/1989  color:gop  text:\"[[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]]\"\n  from: 20/01/1977  till: 20/01/1981  color:dem  text:\"[[Jimmy Carter|Carter]]\"\n  from: 09/08/1974  till: 20/01/1977  color:gop  text:\"[[Gerald Ford|Ford]]\"\n  from: 20/01/1969  till: 09/08/1974  color:gop  text:\"[[Richard Nixon|Nixon]]\"\n  from: 22/11/1963  till: 20/01/1969  color:dem  text:\"[[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]]\"\n  from: 20/01/1961  till: 22/11/1963  color:dem  text:\"[[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]]\"\n  from: 01/01/1953  till: 20/01/1961  color:gop  text:\"[[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]]\"\n  from: 12/04/1945  till: 20/01/1953  color:dem  text:\"[[harry S. Truman|Truman]]\"\n  from: 01/01/1940  till: 12/04/1945  color:dem  text:\"[[Franklin D. Roosevelt|FDR]]\"\n</timeline>\n\n==Strategic partnership==\nThe Strategic partnership characterises the exceptionally close economic and military relations between the two countries. It is specially used for relations since 1952. The United States also actively supports Turkey's membership bid to join the [[European Union]], lobbying frequently on behalf of Ankara through its diplomatic missions in EU capital cities.\n\n=== Cold War (1946-91)===\nFrom 1952 to 1991 the relationship premised upon the concept of a \u201cmutuality of benefits.\u201d <ref name=\"crs.gov\">Jim Zanotti, Turkey-U.S. Defense Cooperation: Prospects and Challenges, April 8, 2011, page 2 Congressional Research Service 7-5700 www.crs.gov R41761</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!colspan =2| Mutuality of benefits\n|-\n|US grantees\n|Turkey grantees\n|-\n|\n# Security guarantees against Soviet. \n|\n# Stationed and base troops and equipment for defensive and intelligence-gathering purposes\n# Grantee on Turkish control (Bosporus and Dardanelles straits) over Soviet access to the Mediterranean \n# Turkish co-belligerency in case of an attack\n# contain Turkish-Greek tensions.\n|}\n\n=== War on Terror (Afghanistan - Iraq - Syria) ===\nBeginning in 2001  the relationship premised upon the concept of [United States foster] cooperation on counterterrorism, law enforcement, and military training and education.<ref>Jim Zanotti, Turkey-U.S. Defense Cooperation: Prospects and Challenges, April 8, 2011, page 3 Congressional Research Service 7-5700 www.crs.gov R41761</ref> Turkey has remained a close ally of the United States, supporting it in the War on Terror in the post-September 11 climate.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!colspan =2| Base of Cooperation<ref name=\"crs.gov\"/> \n|-\n|Turkey Goal: Territorial Integrity \n|US Goal:to achieve stability and a reduced threat of terrorism from Iraq and Afghanistan \n|-\n|\n# ?\n|\n# joint counterterrorism efforts, \n# use of Turkish bases and territory for cargo transport, \n# possible (control-distribution) arms sales, \n# direct involvement of Turkish non-combat troops (in Afghanistan) and trainers.\n|}\n\n=== Dissociation of Partnership===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n!colspan =2| Controversies\n|-\n|US\n|Turkey\n|-\n|\n* [[Iraq War]]: The \"[[hood event]]\" was perceived as an act of U.S. hostility in Turkey.\n* [[Syrian civil war]]: U.S. Support [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) [criticized by Turkey as a Syrian branch of [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] (PKK)] was perceived in Turkey as a hostile activity by [[CENTCOM]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/01/erdogan-operation-syria-afrin-begun-180120120424928.html|title=Erdogan: Operation in Syria's Afrin has begun|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=2018-01-21}}</ref>\n|\n* [[Gulf War]]: Chief of the Turkish General Staff, General [[Necip Torumtay]] resigned to prevent Turkey's active engagement.<ref name=\"Michael Robert Hickok 2000\">Michael Robert Hickok, \u201cHegemon Rising: The Gap Between Turkish Strategy and Military Modernization,\u201d Parameters, vol. 30, no. 2, Summer 2000.</ref>\n* [[Iraq War]]: Turkey denied opening of US ground front (northern front).\n|}\n\nAccording to ''[[The Economist]]'', in October 2017, Turkish-American relations sank to their lowest in over 40 years.<ref name=\"veconomist\" >{{cite news|author=|title=Relations between Turkey and America are near breaking point|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21730102-visa-ban-leads-sharp-deterioration-relations-between-two-nato-allies-relations-between|work=[[The Economist]]|date=9 October 2017}}</ref> Tensions have risen over such issues as America\u2019s 2015-onward openly arming the [[People's Protection Units]] (YPG) while claiming [[Turkey\u2013ISIL conflict|Turkey turned a blind eye]] to ISIL (US led [[Operation Inherent Resolve]] against ISIL began on 15 June 2014. However, Turkey performed [[January 2014 Turkish airstrike in Syria]], which ISIL's response was [[:category:ISIL terrorist incidents in Turkey]]) and other jihadist networks on both sides of its border.<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> The belief among most Turkish citizens that America had a hand in the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] which was compounded by the fact that its suspected ringleader the [[Ulama|Islamic preacher]] [[Hoca]] [[Fethullah Gulen]] lives in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> Shortly after the [[Fethullah\u00e7\u0131 Ter\u00f6r \u00d6rg\u00fct\u00fc|FET\u00d6]] [the Gulen movement] purges-arrests in the country, on October 4, 2016, Turkey moved to arrest Turkish nationals employed at American consulates (Metin Topuz on espionage and conspiracy charges), followed on the October 7, 2016 arrest of a [[pastor]] and a teaching elder of the [[Evangelical Presbyterian Church (United States)|Evangelical Presbyterian]] [[Andrew Brunson]].<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> On October 10, 2016, Turkey declared \u201cWe do not consider the ambassador a representative of the United States\u201d which was a step [[Persona non grata|short of unwanted person]] regarding [[John R. Bass]] (who stand down on October 15, 2017).<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> On May 16, [[2017 clashes at the Turkish Ambassador's Residence in Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\"veconomist\" /> Since the deterioation of the relationships, there is growing Turkish-Russian security cooperation.<ref name=\"veconomist\" />\n\nSeparation of relationships are put on a path by the neoconservative [[John McCain]] National Defense Congressional initiatives plan of The 115th Congress which required the Trump Administration\u2014in the FY2019 John S. McCain National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA, P.L. 115-232)\u2014to report on the status of U.S.-Turkey relations. The Department of Defense (DOD) submitted a mostly classified report to Congress in November 2018 and the following appropriations legislation proposed for FY2019 in the 116 th Congress (H.R. 648) required the DOD report on the issue.<ref>Jim Zanotti, Turkey: Background and U.S. Relations In Brief, February 8, 2019, page i (summary), Congressional Research Service https://crsreports.congress.gov R44000</ref> US untrustful to Turkey bombed its own military base ['reduce usefulness'] during 9\u201317 October [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]] to establish [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |title=US bombs its own military base in Syria to 'reduce usefulness' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-war-trump-turkey-invasion-us-base-bomb-lafarge-cement-factory-manbij-russia-video-a9159851.html |work=The Independent |date=17 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In February 5, 2020, US has halted a secretive military intelligence cooperation program with Turkey against [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] (PKK), which is listed by [[Kurdistan Workers Party/States Listed as Terrorist|US as a terrorist organization]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: U.S. halts secretive drone program with Turkey over Syria incursion |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security-usa-drone-exclusive/exclusive-us-halts-secretive-drone-program-with-turkey-over-syria-incursion-idUSKBN1ZZ1AB |work=Reuters |date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the aftermath of the February 27, 2020 attack performed by the Syrian forces (Russian air support) on Turkish forces, where Turkey had [[Turkish military operation in Idlib Governorate#List of observation posts|observation posts]] in the [[Idlib demilitarization (2018\u20132019)]] zone which holds more than 3,000,000 [[Internally displaced persons in Syria|internally displaced Syrians]] (more than half of them children)<ref>{{cite news |title=U.N. in talks with Turkey to boost Syria aid amid offensive |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-un/u-n-in-talks-with-turkey-to-boost-syria-aid-amid-offensive-idUSKCN20I1XG |work=Reuters |date=24 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> ['There's Nothing Left': Satellite Images<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=&#039;There&#039;s Nothing Left&#039;: Satellite Images Show Razed Villages In Idlib, Syria |url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/theres-nothing-left-satellite-images-show-razed-villages-idlib-syria#stream/0 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=www.wvxu.org |date=4 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> showed the destruction at the refugee camps], military separation between the forces turn into obvious [public] after a senior US State Department official became at odds with the Pentagon over the Turkey's request of two Patriot batteries on its southern border.<ref>{{cite news |last1=SELIGMAN |first1=LARA |title=Pentagon, State Department envoy clash over sending Patriot missiles to Turkey |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/28/turkey-patriot-missiles-pentagon-118256 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=POLITICO |date=28 Feb 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Request confirmed by Turkish Defense Minister Hulusi Akar.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish minister says U.S. may send Patriot systems to Turkey to use in Syria's Idlib |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-usa/turkish-minister-says-us-may-send-patriot-systems-to-turkey-to-use-in-syrias-idlib-idUSKBN20E2LY |work=Reuters |date=20 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> U.S. publicly declared stands by Turkey [no Patriot batteries].<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. says it stands by Turkey after attack on Turkish soldiers in Syria |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-usa/u-s-says-it-stands-by-turkey-after-attack-on-turkish-soldiers-in-syria-idUSKCN20M02I |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=28 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is evident that the Turks do not want to be sidelined by the US or the West when it comes to their own national security concerns. Neither do they want to be hamstrung by easily severed logistics. Clearly they want to be, and have been thinking about becoming, important players in regional politics, and their public national security policy says as much. They have become involved at every opportunity in multi-national military interventions. They have shown a willingness to defy the US. They have industrial and procurement plans aimed at strategic autonomy.<ref>Edward J. Erickson, \u201cTurkey as Regional Hegemon\u20142014: Strategic Implications for the United States,\u201d Turkish Studies, vol. 5, no. 3, autumn 2004</ref> }}\n\n== Public relations==\n[[Turkish Americans]] are Americans whose ancestral origin originates wholly or partly from Turkish descent. According to the [[2000 United States Census]] 117,575 Americans claimed from Republic of Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|author=United States Census Bureau|title=Ancestry: 2000|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/2004pubs/c2kbr-35.pdf|accessdate=2012-05-16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040920132346/http://www.census.gov/prod/2004pubs/c2kbr-35.pdf|archivedate=20 September 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, the actual number of Americans of Turkish descent is believed to be considerably larger as a significant number of ethnic Turks have migrated not just from Republic of Turkey but also from  the [[Balkans]] (such as [[Bulgaria]] and [[North Macedonia]]), [[Cyprus]], and the former [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Karpat|first=Kemal H.|year=2004|chapter=The Turks in America: Historical Background: From Ottoman to Turkish Immigration|title=Studies on Turkish Politics and Society: Selected Articles and Essays|page=627 |place=|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-13322-4 |ref=harv |postscript= <!--None-->}}.</ref> There is a \"[[list of Turkish Americans]]\".\n\n=== Opinion ===\nAccording to a survey conducted in the spring of 2017 and released in August, 72% of the Turks see the United States as a threat to Turkey's security. Furthermore, the United States was perceived as a greater threat to security than Russia or China.<ref>{{cite web|title=72 percent of Turkish citizens see US as security threat|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/72-percent-of-turkish-citizens-see-us-as-security-threat-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=116272&NewsCatID=358|accessdate=2 August 2017|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> According to PBS, opinions of the U.S., in general, dropped steadily from 1999/2000 (Turkey 52% in 1999/2000) and in 2006 favorable opinions dropped significantly in predominately Muslim countries, ranging from 12% in Turkey to 30% in Indonesia and Egypt [the data is from PEW U.S. Image Questionnaire].<ref>{{cite news |title=What Does The World Think of Us? |url=http://www.pbs.org/now/shows/314/opinions-of-us.html |accessdate=19 July 2019 |agency=NOW on PBS |publisher=NPR}}</ref>\n\nHistogram is the percent of Turkey responding favorable to PEW Global Attitudes Survey:<ref>{{cite web |title=Global Indicators Database |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/database/indicator/1/country/TR |website=PEW Research |publisher=Pew Research Center |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n<timeline>\nColors=\n  id:lightgrey value:gray(0.9)\n  id:darkgrey  value:gray(0.8)\n  id:sfondo value:rgb(1,1,1)\n  id:barra value:rgb(0.6,0.7,0.8)\n\nImageSize  = width:680 height:305\nPlotArea   = left:50 bottom:60 top:30 right:30\nDateFormat = x.y\nPeriod     = from:0 till:70\nTimeAxis   = orientation:vertical\nAlignBars  = justify\nScaleMajor = gridcolor:darkgrey increment:20 start:0\nScaleMinor = gridcolor:lightgrey increment:10 start:0\nBackgroundColors = canvas:sfondo\n\nBarData=\n  bar:2000 text:2000\n  bar:2001 text:2001\n  bar:2002 text:2002\n  bar:2003 text:2003\n 